This place is incredible! My sister introduced me to this restaurant via Yelp about 3 years ago when I was in San Francisco. Everytime I'm in San Francisco I always always eat here at least once. Its just that good! First of all you must be prepared for the wait unless you get there right when it opens, honestly who really does that? Be prepared to wait. You will be waiting on the street: there is no waiting area my friend. They offer a great classic turn on the beneit. You can order them stuffed with apples, crawfish or chocolate. My ultimate favorite is the watermelon tea. This isn't the Beyonce watermelon. Ive never had it before I came to brendas and now in a minute I need it in my life! My recommendation would be to try the oyster omelette with toast. My personal favorite is the egg Benedict over catfish. Every meal comes with a homemade biscuits that scream for butter and jelly to your heart's desires! I was definitely Iooking for the person from New Orleans cooking in the kitchen but everyone I saw look like native San Franciscans lol. They got the recipe its my San Francisco love!

SOLID SAN FRANCISCO SOUL-FOOD-SPOT. Brenda's is a great spot if you're craving fried chix, biscuits, gumbo and the likes. But be prepared to wait for it. Unless you come before 11am on a weekday. I have now been twice. The first time I ordered the goat cheese shrimp scramble and an order of beignets. The second time, I ordered a side of fried chicken, gumbo, and a biscuit. The scramble and beignets left much to be desired (this coming from a NOLA-obsessed cade du monde-aholic). I was a bit confused as to what all the Brenda's hype was about. It wasn't until I returned two years later and tried the fried chicken and biscuits, that I saw the light. The fried chicken was flavorful, crunchy, and well-seasoned - just as I like it. The biscuits were fluffy and perfect in that way only biscuits can be. The gumbo was good, but not the best I've ever had. A lot of my satisfaction came from the simple fact that I was able to order all three of these items ala carte and get a much better sampling of the menu as compared to just ordering one main dish. In retrospect, while I was very pleased with my second visit to Brenda's I don't think I would ever wait more than 20 minutes for it. There are many other solid bbq/southern places in San Francisco that you can easily make a res for and have an equally good experience at. While good, it's really not all it's hyped up to be!

My friends and I got there at around 9 AM on a Saturday morning but the wait was surprisingly really short. We ordered the Shrimp & Grits, Clawfish Beignets, Tofu Scramble, and Guava Mimosa. -Shrimp & Grits: AMAZING. I had a bad perception of grits from my first encounter with grits at Roscoes, but this was so different. I definitely recommend everyone to try this dish if it's your first time. -Crawfish Beignets: I loved these as well. It's actually a lot more filling then you would think, and comes with three in each order. It's super flavorful and they don't skimp out on the Crawfish filling. -Tofu Scramble: My vegetarian friend got this and he seemed to really love this! -Guava Mimosa: This was the one item I ordered that I was disappointed in. I love guava and was expecting more of a guava flavor in this mimosa, but it literally tasted like bland soda. There was little to none guava flavor and came in a glass cup like the cups iced water came in :( I would not fork out $7 for this again.

Brenda's is known for their brunch, but regardless of when you go you won't be disappointed! They do some of the best traditional New Orleans food that I've had, with dishes full of flavor and character. I had the shrimp and grits, which came with several pieces of grilled cajun-spiced shrimp on top of a bed of the creamiest cheddar grits. The tomato bacon gravy tied together the entire dish, so every bite had a bit of creamy and a bit of kick. The gumbo was also really good, with the well-developed roux that gives the stew a hearty taste. My boyfriend had the fried chicken, which comes in an extremely generous portion! I loved the fry on the chicken because it was just the right amount of greasy and crunchy without overwhelming your stomach. The crispy skin also had an amazing seasoning on the outside as well. By the end of the meal we were too full to try the beignets, but I'll definitely be back to sample more of the menu!

    Brenda's is a great spot if you're craving fried chix, biscuits, gumbo and the likes. But be prepared to wait for it. Unless you come before 11am on a weekday.

    I have now been twice. The first time I ordered the goat cheese shrimp scramble and an order of beignets. The second time, I ordered a side of fried chicken, gumbo, and a biscuit. The scramble and beignets left much to be desired (this coming from a NOLA-obsessed cade du monde-aholic). I was a bit confused as to what all the Brenda's hype was about. It wasn't until I returned two years later and tried the fried chicken and biscuits, that I saw the light.

    The fried chicken was flavorful, crunchy, and well-seasoned - just as I like it. The biscuits were fluffy and perfect in that way only biscuits can be. The gumbo was good, but not the best I've ever had. A lot of my satisfaction came from the simple fact that I was able to order all three of these items ala carte and get a much better sampling of the menu as compared to just ordering one main dish.

    In retrospect, while I was very pleased with my second visit to Brenda's I don't think I would ever wait more than 20 minutes for it. There are many other solid bbq/southern places in San Francisco that you can easily make a res for and have an equally good experience at. While good, it's really not all it's hyped up to be!

    This food is definitely different, and its nice to try new things! I went on a Sunday with a group of five. We wrote our name down on a chalkboard, played iPhone charades, and were seated within an hour (sorry, I was having too much fun to keep track).

    The place is not big, so seating is a bit cramp. Probably the biggest and weirdest thing that I noticed was that the tables were a bit low for the people sitting on the wall-bench seat. The table was close to the thighs and the wall-bench people were noticeably higher up than the people in chairs across the table.

    I ordered the Pork Belly Cheddar Grits and split a Beignet Sampler with 3 friends. A few at the table ordered the gumbo; I am not a fan but they said it was delicious.

    Thoughts on what I ordered:

    1.Pork Belly Cheddar Grits: Delicious. I haven't had much grits in my life, and when I did, it was at some generic diner (Denny's). For food that has a flatline consistency, I was impressed. If I was a baby, I'd want this in my baby food jars. Pork belly was tender and delicious; a bit fatty but I'd be stupid if I wasn't expecting that.

    2. Beignet Sampler: This dish consisted of 4 beignets, the original, chocolate, apple, and crawfish. Now this is where I felt a little disappointed. I've read plenty of reviews on beignets that raved about them, but to be honest, these tasted dry and just really bread-y. But again, I don't know if I can give them a fair rating on this; maybe I'm just not a beignet person. The chocolate one did stand out as being delicious and more flavorful. Would probably just get that one in the future.

    There's so much food in SF to try. I don't know if I will be back, but I would definitely recommend people to try. Different is nice.
